A larger insight

I think this is actually a missing first-class invariant for the Pantheon:

Every observable artifact is an expression of an underlying generative process.

The Pantheon shouldn’t optimize only for storing artifacts.

It should optimize for recovering the generator that produced them.

That shifts the repository from an archive into an inference engine.

Instead of asking:

“What does this document say?”

it asks:

“What kind of mind, process, environment, or system would have produced this document?”

That’s exactly what a forensic accountant does with transactions, what a systems biologist does with gene expression, what a detective does with evidence, and what the Pantheon could do across every domain. It elevates reconstruction from a specialized capability to a universal epistemic operator.